\chapter*{\centering ABSTRACT}


\vspace{0.3cm}
\textbf{Qauth: A Quantum Secured Authentication Platform} is a security-focused web application designed to strengthen digital authentication by combining conventional identity verification with quantum-inspired key generation and intelligent login-risk analysis. The motivation for the project arises from the growing limitations of classical authentication systems in the presence of credential theft, brute-force attacks, credential stuffing, bot-driven abuse, and the long-term threat posed by quantum computing to existing cryptographic assumptions. The proposed platform addresses these challenges through a layered architecture that integrates secure user management, quantum-key provisioning, anomaly-aware login monitoring, and administrative threat visibility into a unified authentication framework.

The implemented system consists of a React-based frontend, a Django REST backend, a relational persistence layer, and a specialized security engine for quantum-key handling and login anomaly detection. A custom user model is used to manage authentication state, account locking, privilege separation, and failed-login tracking. On successful registration or authenticated login, the platform provisions a per-user quantum key and stores it in encrypted form using AES-256-GCM. The quantum-key pipeline supports three levels of randomness acquisition: true quantum random data through the ANU Quantum Random Number Generator API, a BB84 quantum key distribution simulation as a secondary mechanism, and a cryptographically secure operating-system fallback when external quantum sources are unavailable. To improve entropy conditioning and consistent key derivation, generated randomness is processed using SHA3-256 before secure storage.

In addition to conventional credential-based authentication, the platform implements a quantum challenge-response login demonstration in which a user retrieves a one-time-reveal quantum key, receives a nonce from the server, computes an HMAC-SHA256 proof on the client side, and submits the proof for verification before JWT tokens are issued. This mechanism illustrates how quantum-derived secret material can be incorporated into a stronger authentication workflow beyond static password verification. The backend further records all successful and failed login attempts in an audit log and assigns each attempt a composite risk score based on multiple behavioural indicators such as brute-force activity, excessive request rate from a single IP, credential stuffing patterns, automation-oriented user agents, locked-account access attempts, and unusual login time windows. These signals are aggregated into risk levels that support monitoring, incident analysis, and future adaptive access-control decisions.

The project demonstrates that a modern authentication platform can be enhanced by combining secure software engineering practices, quantum-inspired entropy generation, cryptographic key protection, and behaviour-aware threat detection. The resulting system not only authenticates users but also creates a richer security context around every authentication event, thereby improving resilience, traceability, and administrative awareness. Qauth provides a practical prototype for exploring the intersection of web security, quantum-safe design thinking, and intelligent authentication workflows, while also establishing a strong foundation for future integration with hardware quantum devices, post-quantum cryptographic algorithms, and production-scale threat intelligence systems.
\\\\
\textbf{Keywords:}
Quantum-secured authentication, BB84 simulation, quantum random number generation, anomaly detection, JWT authentication, AES-256-GCM, HMAC challenge-response, audit logging
